    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The main answer is to use File objects. However <a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/io/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Commons IO</a> does have a class <a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-io/apidocs/org/apache/commons/io/FilenameUtils.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">FilenameUtils</a> that can do this kind of thing, such as the <a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-io/apidocs/org/apache/commons/io/FilenameUtils.html#concat%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.String%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">concat()</a> method.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 202319,
      "reputation" : 4758,
      "user_id" : 449325,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/691c3e6cb99976dbbd4dde9c782065ab?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "alpian",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/449325/alpian"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 13,
    "last_activity_date" : 1289741481,
    "creation_date" : 1289741481,
    "answer_id" : 4177678,
    "question_id" : 412380,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>To enhance JodaStephen's answer, Apache Commons IO has FilenameUtils which does this.  Example (on Linux):</p>\n\n<pre><code>assert org.apache.commons.io.FilenameUtils.concat(\"/home/bob\", \"work\\\\stuff.log\") == \"/home/bob/work/stuff.log\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>It's platform independent and will produce whatever separators your system needs.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 153217,
      "reputation" : 536,
      "user_id" : 368316,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d4eeac49379a522732180e2985aa3ee9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Bill",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/368316/bill"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1370253548,
    "last_edit_date" : 1370253548,
    "creation_date" : 1291747006,
    "answer_id" : 4380310,
    "question_id" : 412380,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here's a solution which handles multiple path parts and edge conditions:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public static String combinePaths(String ... paths)\n{\n  if ( paths.length == 0)\n  {\n    return \"\";\n  }\n\n  File combined = new File(paths[0]);\n\n  int i = 1;\n  while ( i &lt; paths.length)\n  {\n    combined = new File(combined, paths[i]);\n    ++i;\n  }\n\n  return combined.getPath();\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 191354,
      "reputation" : 18177,
      "user_id" : 431880,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 98,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22325a44a43fd0f6e4dffccd09e78c85?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "isNaN1247",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/431880/isnan1247"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 18,
    "last_activity_date" : 1328434275,
    "creation_date" : 1328434275,
    "answer_id" : 9148215,
    "question_id" : 412380,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I know its a long time since Jon's original answer, but I had a similar requirement to the OP. </p>\n\n<p>By way of extending Jon's solution I came up with the following, which will take one or more path segments takes as many path segments that you can throw at it.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Usage</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>Path.combine(\"/Users/beardtwizzle/\");\nPath.combine(\"/\", \"Users\", \"beardtwizzle\");\nPath.combine(new String[] { \"/\", \"Users\", \"beardtwizzle\", \"arrayUsage\" });\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Code here for others with a similar problem</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Path {\n    public static String combine(String... paths)\n    {\n        File file = new File(paths[0]);\n\n        for (int i = 1; i &lt; paths.length ; i++) {\n            file = new File(file, paths[i]);\n        }\n\n        return file.getPath();\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
